            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410503098,
            "creation_date": 1410502652,
            "body": "<p>You can't do that.<\/p>\n\n<p>Valid one is<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String newData = getData().toString();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can't get <code>Object<\/code> back from <code>toString()<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>You can use <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/io/Serializable.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Serialization<\/a>. But that is not the thing you are asking.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also you can be smart as following. Using <code>JSon<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>@Override\npublic String toString() {\n   return new Gson().toJson(this);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now you can get Object back<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String str=myClass.toString();\nMyClass myClass=new Gson().fromJson(str,MyClass.class);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25801929,
            "question_id": 25801870,
            "last_edit_date": 1410503098
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f0232a180c17d816473f0f87c4af978?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 721943,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 659501,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/659501/danarl",
                "reputation": 1143,
                "display_name": "DanArl"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410502602,
            "creation_date": 1410502602,
            "body": "<p>If <strong>getData()<\/strong> was returning the object before it should still return the object.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25801918,
            "question_id": 25801870
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/pX6ku.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1275953,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1231230,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1231230/ankur-singhal",
                "reputation": 26120,
                "display_name": "Ankur Singhal",
                "accept_rate": 76
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410502586,
            "creation_date": 1410502586,
            "body": "<p>No you cannot.<\/p>\n\n<p><code>toString()<\/code> is only intended for <code>logging<\/code> and <code>debug<\/code> purposes. It is not intended for <code>serializing<\/code> the <code>state of an Object<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If the object in question supports <code>serialization<\/code> then go with <code>serialization<\/code> and <code>deserialization<\/code> to find out how to do this.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25801914,
            "question_id": 25801870
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/tr7wR.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2524075,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2193767,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2193767/thelostmind",
                "reputation": 36294,
                "display_name": "TheLostMind",
                "accept_rate": 78
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410503047,
            "creation_date": 1410503047,
            "body": "<p>You cannot get the same object back. But what you can do is, you can create a new object with the same value(s) as the original one by removing each parameter of the returned String. For that you will have to ensure that you are getting all the parameters of the object in the returned string. <\/p>\n\n<p>Overall, a very bad idea.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802012,
            "question_id": 25801870
        }
